        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName><hi rend="print">Down, | Beckenham, Kent.</hi></placeName>
                    <date>March 17<hi rend="superscript">th</hi> 1874</date>
                    <salute>Dear Sir</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>I thank you for your extremely kind letter. However much you may have criticised my views in your book, I feel sure from your frank &amp; generous remarks, that I shall have no just cause to complain.<ref target="#foot.f1"/> But as I have viewed all natural objects for above 30 years under the light of Natural Selection, it is not likely that any arguments, short of demonstration, would convince me that my views are altogether erroneous.<ref target="#foot.f2"/> I am sorry to say that I have to add that your book has not arrived, but only its cover. You will see in the inclosed, printed on it “found in N.P.B. (North Post Bag) without contents”. Pray do not inconvenience yourself by sending me another copy, as I can easily procure one from my booksellers.<ref target="#foot.f3"/></p>
<p>Pray believe me with much respect | Dear Sir | yours faithfully | Charles Darwin</p> 
                </div>
            </div>

            
            
        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">Wigand had sent CD the first volume of his book <hi rend="italic">Der Darwinismus und die Naturforschung Newtons und Cuviers</hi> (‘Darwinism and the natural researches of Newton and Cuvier’; <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_8760.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Wigand 1874–7</ref>). See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-9352.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from Albert Wigand, 11 March 1874</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-9352.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from Albert Wigand, 11 March 1874</ref> and n. 3.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">All three volumes of <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_8760.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Wigand 1874–7</ref> are in the Darwin Library–Down.</note>
        </div>        
            
